    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-09-21T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-09-21T15:00:00-05:00" n="557"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d557">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.01 Foreign Control/367: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Geneva (<persName corresp="#p_VSRG1" type="to"
                        >Gilbert</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-09-21T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 21, 1932—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>132. For <persName corresp="#p_RSJ1">Reber</persName>. Your 250, September 20, 3
                    p.m., was received after the dispatch of our No. 130.<note n="68"
                        xml:id="d557fn68">No. 130 not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Your message makes it appear that the Committee is endeavoring to exact our
                    approval of a “neutral” Chief Adviser as the price of support for our position
                    with reference to the necessity of the delegation <pb facs="0844" n="754"
                        xml:id="pg_754"/> of authority. We query, as stated last night, whether the
                    question of the nationality of the principal official should properly come up at
                    this time. If the Committee insists upon bringing it up, and if you are unable
                    to reserve our position thereon, you will have to state that your Government,
                    the interests of whose nationals represent by far the most important investment
                    in Liberia, would energetically support the appointment of an American
                    citizen.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
